{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos386.erdos_386 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos386.erdos_386.","id":"vf_315ea700d07e802a","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #386: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $2\\leq k\\leq n-2$. Can $\\binom{n}{k}$ be the product of consecutive primes infinitely often? For example\\[\\binom{21}{2}=2\\cdot 3\\cdot 5\\cdot 7.\\] Current best: Erd\\H{o}s and Graham write that 'a proof that this cannot happen infinitely often for $\\binom{n}{2}$ seems hopeless; probably this can never happen for $\\binom{n}{k}$ if $3\\leq k\\leq n-3$.'  Weisenberg has provided four easy examples that show Erd\\H{o}s and Graham were too optimistic here:\\[\\binom{7}{3}=5\\cdot 7,\\]\\[\\binom{10}{4}= 2\\cdot 3\\cdot 5\\cdot 7,\\]\\[\\binom{14}{4} = 7\\cdot 11\\cdot 13,\\]and\\[\\binom{15}{6}=5\\cdot 7\\cdot 11\\cdot 13.\\]The known values of $n$ for which $\\binom{n}{2}$ is the product of consecutive primes are $4,6,15,21,715$ (see A280992). Prize: no. OEIS: A280992. Tags: binomial coefficients, number theory.","id":"vf_fa3012778a623e8f","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/386.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_315ea700d07e802a","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:386","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_315ea700d07e802a","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"vf_fa3012778a623e8f","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem i